Simon Willison highlights “Agentic Engineering Practices”, arguing that by late 2023 AI‑coding agents become production tools. He shows a workflow combining red‑green test‑driven development, reusable project templates, and executable validation—spinning up servers and probing APIs to automatically confirm agent output. The approach cuts manual review effort, accelerates prototype‑to‑deploy cycles, and reduces flaky code in Kubernetes‑based pipelines.  

### [Pretext](https://simonwillison.net/2026/Mar/29/pretext/#atom-everything) — Simon Willison  
Pretext is a lightweight browser library that calculates rendered height of line‑wrapped, multi‑language text without touching the DOM. It precomputes word metrics once via an off‑screen canvas, then performs fast layout calls at a given width, avoiding costly DOM reflows. Validation against *The Great Gatsby* and large public‑domain corpora across Thai, Chinese, Korean, Japanese, Arabic, and RTL scripts demonstrates high accuracy. For ML infra teams, this pattern of “prepare once, layout cheaply” can reduce client‑side rendering overhead in inference dashboards or real‑time labeling UIs.  

### [Python Vulnerability Lookup](https://simonwillison.net/2026/Mar/29/python-vulnerability-lookup/#atom-everything) — Simon Willison  
A lightweight HTML tool that queries OSV.dev’s open‑source vulnerability database directly from the browser. By parsing a `pyproject.toml`, `requirements.txt`, or GitHub repo name, it sends package names to OSV.dev’s CORS‑enabled API and displays vulnerabilities in a table. This client‑side approach eliminates the need for a backend proxy, enabling quick dependency checks before building container images or deploying models. It supports DevSecOps practices by catching known issues early in the ML pipeline.